📑 Mission Report: HTB - Machine "Dancing"

Target IP: 10.129.54.233

Difficulty: Easy / Starting Point

Skill Focus: SMB Enumeration, Null Sessions, Remote File System Navigation.
🔍 Phase 1: Reconnaissance (Enumeration)

The initial nmap scan revealed that the target is a Windows machine with the SMB (Server Message Block) protocol active on port 445.
Bash

nmap -sV 10.129.54.233
# Result: 445/tcp open microsoft-ds

🛠️ Phase 2: Vulnerability Assessment

I attempted to list the network shares using an Anonymous Login (Null Session). The server misconfiguration allowed me to view the internal share structure without providing credentials.
Bash

smbclient -L 10.129.54.233

Findings:

    ADMIN$, C$, IPC$: Standard administrative shares.

    WorkShares: A custom user-defined share, likely containing sensitive data.

🏴‍☠️ Phase 3: Exploitation & Data Exfiltration

Using smbclient, I established a connection to the WorkShares directory.

    Access: Connected anonymously to //10.129.54.233/WorkShares.

    Navigation: Explored user directories (Amy.J, James.P).

    Discovery: Found the target file flag.txt inside the James.P directory.

    Exfiltration: Successfully downloaded the flag to my local attack machine using the get command.

Bash

smb: \James.P\> get flag.txt

💡 Key Takeaway (eJPT Concept)

This lab demonstrates the danger of Insecure SMB Share Permissions. In a corporate environment, allowing anonymous access to work directories can lead to massive data leaks and credential harvesting.
